<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnostic description">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnostic description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Mandible lacinia mobilis a stemmed, distally expanded, irregularly cusped blade; palp article 2 broadened. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Maxilla 2</emphasis>
inner plate longer than outer plate; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">outer plate with extremely long distally barbed slender setae</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Gnathopod 1 coxa margins diverging distally</emphasis>
. Pereopod 5 coxa slightly wider than long; basis greatly expanded posteriorly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Western Atlantic. Mediterranean Sea. Japan. Australia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Found in shallow warm seas. A scavenger, also found in dead spatangoid tests.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Previously, the setal fringe on the distal margins of the coxae from gnathopod 1 to pereopod 4 was considered to be a diagnostic character of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1911" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Here we exclude that character from the diagnosis of the genus, as the setal fringe is absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Takekawa &amp; Ishimaru" baseAuthorityYear="2000" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui onagawae" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onagawae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui onagawae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Takekawa &amp; Ishimaru, 2000), comb. n. Instead, we consider the unusual long, distally barbed setae on the outer plate of maxilla 2 to be an autapomorphy that distinguishes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chevreux" authorityYear="1911" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all other genera in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowry &amp; Stoddart" authorityYear="1997" family="Scopelocheiridae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="family">Scopelocheiridae</taxonomicName>
. See 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kilgallen &amp; Lowry" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Takekawa &amp; Ishimaru" baseAuthorityYear="2000" class="Malacostraca" family="Scopelocheiridae" genus="Aroui" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aroui onagawae" order="Amphipoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="onagawae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aroui onagawae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, below, for further discussion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
